Here is the updated step-by-step process for a fresh NixOS install using your GitHub repository, configured specifically for Btrfs with standard subvolumes (root, home, and nix) to allow for easy snapshots. [1] 
## 1. Partition, Format, and Mount Disks (Btrfs Layout)
Boot into the live ISO, open a terminal, and prepare your drive (assuming /dev/nvme0n1—adjust to your actual drive name). [2] 

* Partition the drive:
Run cfdisk /dev/nvme0n1. Create a GPT partition table with:
* A 512MB–1GB EFI partition (type: EFI System).
   * A Root partition using the remaining space (type: Linux filesystem). [3, 4] 
* Format the partitions:

mkfs.vfat -F 32 -n boot /dev/nvme0n1p1
mkfs.btrfs -L nixos /dev/nvme0n1p2

* Create and mount Btrfs subvolumes:
Mount the main Btrfs partition temporarily to create your subvolume structure:

mount /dev/nvme0n1p2 /mnt
btrfs subvolume create /mnt/@
btrfs subvolume create /mnt/@home
btrfs subvolume create /mnt/@nix
umount /mnt

[5, 6] 
* Mount subvolumes with optimization flags:
Mount your new subvolumes into their proper relative directories under /mnt:

# Mount root subvolume
mount -o subvol=@,compress=zstd,noatime /dev/nvme0n1p2 /mnt
# Create directories for other mounts
mkdir -p /mnt/{home,nix,boot}
# Mount home and nix subvolumes
mount -o subvol=@home,compress=zstd,noatime /dev/nvme0n1p2 /mnt/home
mount -o subvol=@nix,compress=zstd,noatime /dev/nvme0n1p2 /mnt/nix
# Mount the EFI boot partition
mount /dev/nvme0n1p1 /mnt/boot

[7] 

## 2. Generate the Hardware Configuration
NixOS will automatically scan your subvolume setup and write the correct mount options into the configuration.

* Run the generation command:

nixos-generate-config --root /mnt

* This creates hardware-configuration.nix inside /mnt/etc/nixos/. You can safely ignore or delete the auto-generated configuration.nix.

## 3. Clone Your GitHub Repository

* Move into the installation configuration folder:

cd /mnt/etc/nixos

* Clone your configuration repository directly into this folder:

git clone <your-github-repo-url> .

(Note the . at the end to clone files directly into the current directory).

## 4. Integrate and Stage the Hardware File

* Verify flake.nix: Ensure your target nixosSystem modules list includes ./hardware-configuration.nix.
* Stage the file in Git: Nix flakes strictly ignore untracked files. Because the hardware configuration is brand new, you must tell Git about it, or the installer will act like it does not exist:

git add hardware-configuration.nix


## 5. Install NixOS

* Run the installation script pointing directly to your flake and specific hostname:

nixos-install --flake .#<your-hostname>

Replace <your-hostname> with the specific attribute name defined under nixosConfigurations in your flake.nix.

## 6. Reboot

* Set a root password if prompted, unmount the drives, and reboot:

reboot


